"# Chapter 12 — The CPU: fetch, decode, execute — and loop forever

You have everything. Gates (chapter 5). Adders (chapter 6, 7). Memory
(chapter 8, 9). State machines (chapter 10). ALU (chapter 11). All that
is left is to wire them together and tell the machine what to do.

That is a CPU. This chapter builds a tiny one.

## The Von Neumann architecture

In 1945, John von Neumann wrote a report called *First Draft of a
Report on the EDVAC* while consulting on the EDVAC computer at the
University of Pennsylvania. In it he described what everybody now calls
the **Von Neumann architecture**:

- A single memory that stores both instructions and data.
- A CPU that reads instructions from that memory, one after another.
- The CPU has a program counter, a small register file, and an ALU.
- The CPU executes each instruction by decoding it and performing the
  operation it names.

Almost every computer since 1945 has been Von Neumann. The main
alternative is called the **Harvard architecture**, which uses
separate memories for instructions and data — that shows up in
embedded processors, digital signal processors, and some CPU cache
designs. But mostly, Von Neumann won.

## The instruction cycle — the big loop

Every CPU repeats this loop forever, from the moment it is powered on
to the moment it is switched off:

```
   FOREVER:
     1. Fetch the next instruction from memory (address = PC).
     2. Increment PC (so it points at the instruction after this one).
     3. Decode the instruction — figure out what it means.
     4. Execute — do what the instruction says.
     5. Write back — save the result to a register or memory.
     6. Go to step 1.
```

That is the fetch-decode-execute cycle. Alfred asked me to point at
this specifically. **This is the biggest, most fundamental loop in
this book.** Every action your computer takes is one turn of this
loop, on some CPU somewhere, right now.

**ASCII diagram of the instruction cycle:**

```
         +-------------------------+
         |                         |
         v                         |
   +-----------+                   |
   |  Fetch    |                   |
   |  (mem@PC) |                   |
   +-----------+                   |
         |                         |
         v                         |
   +-----------+                   |
   |  PC += 1  |                   |
   +-----------+                   |
         |                         |
         v                         |
   +-----------+                   |
   |  Decode   |                   |
   +-----------+                   |
         |                         |
         v                         |
   +-----------+                   |
   |  Execute  |                   |
   |  (ALU op) |                   |
   +-----------+                   |
         |                         |
         v                         |
   +-----------+                   |
   |  Writeback|                   |
   +-----------+-------------------+
```

Follow the arrow at the end back to the top. That is the whole game.

## A tiny CPU — the plan

We are going to build a tiny CPU in Motoi Scheme. It has:

- Four 8-bit registers, named 0, 1, 2, 3.
- An 8-bit program counter (PC).
- 256 bytes of memory (both program and data live here).
- An 8-instruction ISA (instruction set).
- Zero, negative, and carry flags.

The instructions:

```
  0  NOP                 do nothing
  1  LDI r, imm          load immediate: r = imm
  2  MOV rD, rS          rD = rS
  3  ADD rD, rS          rD = rD + rS  (with flags)
  4  SUB rD, rS          rD = rD - rS  (with flags)
  5  JMP addr            PC = addr
  6  JZ  addr            if Z flag, PC = addr
  7  HALT                stop the machine
```

Each instruction is one byte for the opcode plus one or two bytes for
operands. We will encode as lists of symbols for readability; a real
CPU packs them tightly in binary.

## The CPU in Motoi Scheme

Let us build it. First, memory:

```
(define (make-memory size)
  (let ((cells (make-vector size 0)))
    (lambda (msg . args)
      (cond
        ((eq? msg 'read)
         (vector-ref cells (car args)))
        ((eq? msg 'write)
         (vector-set! cells (car args) (cadr args))
         'wrote)))))

(define mem (make-memory 256))
```

Now a register file (simpler than chapter 9's — just a vector):

```
(define (make-regs count)
  (let ((r (make-vector count 0)))
    (lambda (msg . args)
      (cond
        ((eq? msg 'read)
         (vector-ref r (car args)))
        ((eq? msg 'write)
         (vector-set! r (car args) (cadr args))
         'wrote)))))

(define regs (make-regs 4))
```

Now the CPU itself. State: PC, flags, plus the memory and regs:

```
(define (make-cpu mem regs)
  (let ((pc     0)
        (z-flag #f)
        (n-flag #f)
        (halted #f))

    (define (fetch-byte)
      (let ((b (mem 'read pc)))
        (set! pc (+ pc 1))
        b))

    (define (set-flags result)
      ;; treat result as 8-bit; wrap into 0..255
      (let ((w (modulo result 256)))
        (set! z-flag (= w 0))
        (set! n-flag (>= w 128))
        w))

    (define (step)
      (if halted
          'halted
          (let ((op (fetch-byte)))
            (case op
              ((0)   'nop)                                          ;; NOP
              ((1)                                                  ;; LDI r, imm
               (let ((r (fetch-byte)) (v (fetch-byte)))
                 (regs 'write r v)))
              ((2)                                                  ;; MOV rD, rS
               (let ((rd (fetch-byte)) (rs (fetch-byte)))
                 (regs 'write rd (regs 'read rs))))
              ((3)                                                  ;; ADD rD, rS
               (let* ((rd (fetch-byte)) (rs (fetch-byte))
                      (sum (+ (regs 'read rd) (regs 'read rs)))
                      (w (set-flags sum)))
                 (regs 'write rd w)))
              ((4)                                                  ;; SUB rD, rS
               (let* ((rd (fetch-byte)) (rs (fetch-byte))
                      (diff (- (regs 'read rd) (regs 'read rs)))
                      (w (set-flags diff)))
                 (regs 'write rd w)))
              ((5)                                                  ;; JMP addr
               (let ((a (fetch-byte)))
                 (set! pc a)))
              ((6)                                                  ;; JZ addr
               (let ((a (fetch-byte)))
                 (if z-flag (set! pc a))))
              ((7)                                                  ;; HALT
               (set! halted #t))
              (else (error 'unknown-opcode op))))))

    (define (run max-steps)
      (let loop ((n 0))
        (cond
          (halted 'halted)
          ((>= n max-steps) 'out-of-steps)
          (else
            (step)
            (loop (+ n 1))))))

    (lambda (msg . args)
      (cond
        ((eq? msg 'step)  (step))
        ((eq? msg 'run)   (run (car args)))
        ((eq? msg 'pc)    pc)
        ((eq? msg 'z)     z-flag)
        ((eq? msg 'n)     n-flag)
        ((eq? msg 'halted?) halted)
        ((eq? msg 'reset) (set! pc 0) (set! halted #f) 'reset)))))

(define cpu (make-cpu mem regs))
```

That is a CPU. Reads instructions from memory. Executes them. Increments
PC. Sets flags. Can jump. Can halt.

## Running a program

Let us write a program that adds 5 and 3 and stores the result in
register 0. In our encoding, the byte sequence is:

```
   LDI 0, 5       ->   [1  0  5]
   LDI 1, 3       ->   [1  1  3]
   ADD 0, 1       ->   [3  0  1]
   HALT           ->   [7]
```

Total: eight bytes. Let us load them into memory and run:

```
;; program bytes at address 0
(mem 'write 0 1) (mem 'write 1 0) (mem 'write 2 5)   ;; LDI 0, 5
(mem 'write 3 1) (mem 'write 4 1) (mem 'write 5 3)   ;; LDI 1, 3
(mem 'write 6 3) (mem 'write 7 0) (mem 'write 8 1)   ;; ADD 0, 1
(mem 'write 9 7)                                     ;; HALT

(cpu 'reset)
(cpu 'run 100)   ;; => halted
(regs 'read 0)   ;; => 8
```

Register 0 holds 8. That is 5 + 3, computed by our CPU, by walking
through fetch-decode-execute four times (three instructions plus the
HALT).

## A loop in machine code

Now let us do something loopier. Count down from 5 to 0 and stop when
we hit zero.

Program:

```
   LDI 0, 5           ; register 0 = 5
   LDI 1, 1           ; register 1 = 1
   ; loop:
   SUB 0, 1           ; r0 = r0 - 1, sets Z if result 0
   JZ  0x0B           ; if Z, jump to HALT at address 11
   JMP 0x06           ; otherwise, jump back to SUB
   ; halt:
   HALT
```

Let us encode. LDI takes 3 bytes. SUB takes 3. JZ and JMP take 2 each.
HALT is 1.

```
   addr  0: LDI 0, 5   ->  [1 0 5]
   addr  3: LDI 1, 1   ->  [1 1 1]
   addr  6: SUB 0, 1   ->  [4 0 1]
   addr  9: JZ  0x0D   ->  [6 13]
   addr 11: JMP 0x06   ->  [5 6]
   addr 13: HALT       ->  [7]
```

Load and run:

```
(let ((bytes '(1 0 5   1 1 1   4 0 1   6 13   5 6   7)))
  (let loop ((i 0) (bs bytes))
    (if (null? bs) 'loaded
        (begin (mem 'write i (car bs))
               (loop (+ i 1) (cdr bs))))))

(cpu 'reset)
(cpu 'run 100)      ;; => halted
(regs 'read 0)      ;; => 0
(cpu 'pc)           ;; => 14
```

The program looped five times, subtracting 1 each pass. On the sixth
pass, register 0 became 0, which set the Z flag, which triggered the
JZ, which jumped to the HALT.

**That is a loop written in machine code, executed by a CPU we built.**

Every `while` loop, every `for` loop, every recursion in every language
you know eventually compiles down to something that looks essentially
like this: a comparison, a conditional branch, and an unconditional
branch back to the start.

## The clock and the loop, from all sides

The CPU as a whole is a state machine with three main states:

- **fetch:** read a byte from memory@PC.
- **decode-and-execute:** figure out what the byte means and do it.
- **writeback:** update the register or memory or PC.

Each clock cycle, the state advances. When the state machine returns
to `fetch`, we call that an **instruction cycle** or **instruction
retirement.** Modern CPUs retire multiple instructions per clock cycle
through pipelining and superscalar tricks; but the basic idea is the
loop we just wrote.

Our CPU runs at whatever speed Motoi's REPL runs at — maybe millions
of instructions per second. A real CPU runs at billions of instructions
per second. Twenty-thousand-year jump from Ishango: same primitive
counting operation, executed a hundred billion times a second, on
sixty-four bits at a time.

## What real CPUs add on top

Our CPU is deliberately tiny. Real CPUs add:

- **Pipelining:** overlap fetch, decode, execute of consecutive
  instructions.
- **Superscalar:** multiple ALUs, so two instructions can execute at
  once if they don't depend on each other.
- **Out-of-order execution:** decode a batch of instructions, execute
  them in whatever order dependencies allow, then commit results in
  order.
- **Branch prediction:** guess whether a branch will be taken so you
  can start fetching the target early.
- **Cache:** small fast memory close to the CPU, so you don't wait for
  main RAM (chapter 13).
- **Interrupts:** external signals that can pause the current program,
  jump to a handler, then resume.
- **Virtual memory:** page tables so each program sees its own memory
  space.
- **Privilege levels:** kernel mode vs. user mode.

All of these are polish on the fetch-decode-execute loop. The loop is
still there. It is still what makes the whole thing go.

## The 6502

I want to name one specific CPU because Motoi loves it: the **MOS 6502**,
released by MOS Technology in 1975. It was designed by Chuck Peddle
and a small team. It cost $25 in a marketplace where similar chips
cost $150.

The 6502 had:

- Three 8-bit registers: A (accumulator), X, Y (indexes).
- An 8-bit stack pointer.
- A 16-bit program counter.
- Status flags: N, V, B, D, I, Z, C.
- 56 official instructions.
- About 3,510 transistors.

It ran at 1 to 2 MHz. It fits in a 40-pin dual in-line package that
sits comfortably on a hobbyist's breadboard.

The 6502 shipped in the Apple II, the Commodore 64, the Atari 800, the
BBC Micro, and the Nintendo Entertainment System, among many others.
Every one of those machines executed the fetch-decode-execute loop
about a million times a second, and out of that came *Super Mario Bros*
and *Elite* and *Karateka* and *SICP-in-BASIC*. The Book of Computing
in this repo goes into more depth on the 6502; see chapter 4 of that
book for context.

## The loop appears — this is where it lives

Everything else in this book is subordinate to the CPU loop. The clock
ticks. The PC increments. The instruction retires. Repeat.

Appendix E of this book is dedicated to the fact that this loop
underlies everything. Read it.

## What Motoi wants you to take from this

- A CPU is a state machine that fetches, decodes, executes, and
  loops forever.
- Every program you have ever run is a sequence of bytes that this
  state machine walks through.
- Loops in your programs correspond to branches in the machine code
  that send the PC back to an earlier address.
- We built one. In Scheme. It runs. Now go build a bigger one.

## Next

Chapter 13: not all memory is equal. Cache, DRAM, disk. Why the same
program can run 1000× slower depending on where its data sits.
")
